{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_fogler_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532610/1921031401/0403.xml":{"full_text":"The Wise Use\nof the facilities of a\nmodern bank are of\nmaterial assistance\nto the business man\nwho desires to build*\nsolidly and well.\nWe are hecdquarlc: s\nfor our clierls.\nNATIONAL BANK\n23ro Street, where\nFIFTH AVENUE\nCROSSES BROADWAY\nAmerica Holds Key to Reparations\nTangle's Solution, Says Withers\nShould This Nation Accept German Ohligalions\nin Payment for European Debt, Problem Would\nBe Easily Settled; Situation Dark, He Adds\nBy Hartley Withers\nEditor of The Economist\nSr'cia! Cable to The Tribune\nCopyright, *19*n. New York Tribuns 3n<i.\nLONDON*, March 13.?It is small\n1 wonder that President Harding takes\nan unfavorable attitude toward\nI European entanglements considering\nthe silly mess abroad and the position\nproduced by European statesmanship.\nEuropean politics and diplomacy\nhave generally been g tangle of am?\nbitions and chicanery and British in\ntcrvention, and these have left a big\nburden of debt, largely due to money\nspent in hiring Europeans to fight for\ntheir own liberty and England's\nagainst European despots.\nApologists for the British policy say\nthat they had no choice, owing to the\nproximity of England to the Continent.\nThis may be true.\nBut the London conference fiasco has\nproduced a ridiculous situation. Both\nsides bluffed high and called each\nother's bluff. Now neither side has\nwinning cards and pretends it is not\ngoing to play any. more.\nGerman Proposals Unacceptable\nThe German proposals made last\nMonday could hardly have been enter?\ntained, as they settled things only for\nfive years, involving a fresh deal then.\nOn paper the plan did not look so bad,\nbecause in five years it would be much\neasier to arrive at a fair estimate of\nGermany's capacity to pay, bu*^ ob?\nviously it would be impossible to\nleave the settlement so long incom\nI plete.\nGermany's request to be allowed n\nI\nThe Week's B