ew ti^v- than to throw back the whole\nquestion of settlement by stopping the\nconference, occupying German towns\nasid start i iig othc r acl ma,\nGermans Made Mistake\nrrobably the Germans thought that\n?the Allies wouid 1?\" so eager for a set?\ntlement that any terms offered would\nbo accepted. They naturally had to be\ndisabused of this view, but this might\nhave been done more effectively and\nby less cos? !y methods,\nIt is gen? rail h c\\ ed here that the\narbitrary Allied titude was adepte?!\nin deference t<> the position of the\n?French jroverrimoi.t, which, it was sup?\nposed, would have I e o r i jeopardized if\ni the conference continued to drag along.\nOpinion in- business circiea asid.'\nfrom the extreme jingo drumbeaters,\ni who are now in the scanty minority\nwas that of exasperation over the con\ntinued delay in arriving at a definite\n'settlement, which, it wan acknowledged\nby Premier Lloyd George in h;s con?\nference speech, is essential to peace.\nEssential for Trade Revival\nEverybody now sees that peace is\nessential for any ti reco?\ncry, return to prosperity and reduction\nof taxation.\nMuch amusement ?and exasperation,\nalso?was caused by the proposal to\nmake British purchasers of German\ngoods pay half of the coal price to e\nBritish government and hand ti treas\nury receipt to the German seller, who\nwould le pe d to illect tl sum\nfrom t he Gi i. a n gover\nu vvould ake Ai glo\nGerman trade exl ren ffic It and\ndivert German goods, to other coun\ntrie'l.\nThua the* devious measure would af\nCord protection, bo much welcomed by\nthose who want, to shut out German\ngoods, but other effects would be more\nserious, since German goods would be\nforced to seek neutral markets in com?\npet?! ion with British exports, and the\nwhole British trade with nil other coun?\ntries would be hampered by the neces?\nsity of certificates of origin showing\n(hat the goods entering were not Ger?\nman.\nAll kinds of complicated questions\nalso arise respecting international\ncredit raisrd in London by neutral\nhanks to he used in financing the trans?\nfer of German goods.\nMay Have German Origin\nIt. is suggested that this scheme has\na German origin, and this is the best\nexplanation for the production of n\nmeasure that would damage Groat i\nBritain more than Germany could.\nEverybody wants Germany to pay the\nfull bill o? damages done, but the Allied\nmeasures arc quite ineffectual to pro?\nduce a substantial payment and only\nprolong the period of uncertainty and\nbitterness and check trade at a time\ncf serious depression and unemploy?\nment.\nBoth parties want an agreed settle?\nment that wi*,l work. Enforced settle\nmi nt, it is agreed, will not work.\nGermany's strength lies in the fact\nthat no nation can be forced to work\nagainst its will.\nThe strength of the Allied position\nlies in the fact that there is greater\nurgency of an effective and immediate\nsettlement for Germany than for the\nAllies.\nThe only satisfactory solution to\nthis problem is one by which the total\nAllied claim against Germany can be\ncapitalized at its present value and\nexpressed indefinitely in acceptable\nobligations.\nAn excellent solution would be af?\nforded if America could be induced\nto accept the German obligation in\npayment of Europe's debts, each\nEuropean power guaranteeing its pro?\nportion of the German obligation. But\nil is doubtful if this proposal would be\n:ceptable to your public, which natui\nally si suspicious of European finan?\ncial pro]' ?als after the regrettable at?\ntempt to induce America to cancel the\nA?ied war debts.\nAltogether the financial position\nhere shows marked improvement in the\nreduction in the rate on Treasury\nbi 113 from 6Y2 to 6 per cent.\nThe industrial outlook, on the other\nland, is still bad.\nEstimates of the government's re?\nquirements for expenditures in the\n.7 fiscal year foreshadow a reduc?\ntion, but it is doubtful v,*ii'*thcr a bud\n0f ?960,000,000 v ill bo possible.\nW